"n.突如其来的大灾难 【英】 n. 突如其来的大灾难(su dden great disaster ) 【考】 catastrophe : mishap / humiliation : embarrassment(灾难比不幸程度深/ 羞辱比窘迫程度深) 【例】 The earthquake was a terrible catastrophe . n. (突如其来的、涉及面广的)大灾难 = disaster; (彻底的)失败 【例】The English party turned out to be a catastrophe 英语晚会的结局糟透了. 【记】cata向下, strophe翻转－天向下翻转－塌下来了－大灾难 【参】catastrophic(adj 悲惨的, 灾难的) 【类】catastrophe: mishap = humiliation: embarrassment大灾难是特彆不幸 = 羞辱是特别窘迫oxymoron: contradictory = mishap: catastrophic矛盾修饰法是矛盾的 = 不幸是灾难的 【记】cata + strop 向下一拽皮带，结果把天弄塌了 catastrophe (n.)  1530s, ""reversal of what is expected"" (especially a fatal turning point in a drama), from Latin catastropha, from Greek katastrophe ""an overturning; a sudden end,"" from katastrephein ""to overturn, turn down, trample on; to come to an end,"" from kata ""down"" (see cata-) + strephein ""turn"" (see strophe). Extension to ""sudden disaster"" is first recorded 1748."
